  <!-- ============ BURN PERMITS ============ -->
  <section class="block cream" id="permits">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head">
        <div>
          <h2>Open burning in Ira</h2>
          <p class="blurb">
            By Vermont state law (10 V.S.A. &sect; 2646), any open burning of natural wood
            or brush on your property requires a written permit from the town Fire Warden.
            Permits are free. We issue them day-of based on current conditions.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- 4-quadrant rules -->
      <div class="permit-grid">
        <div>
          <div class="permit-num">01</div>
          <h3>What you can burn</h3>
          <p>
            Natural wood, brush, leaves, and untreated lumber grown or cut on your own
            property. Material must be dry and piled no larger than 4 ft &times; 4 ft
            &times; 4 ft.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="permit-num">02</div>
          <h3>What is never allowed</h3>
          <p>
            Household trash, treated wood, tires, plastics, construction debris, or any
            material hauled in from off-site. No exceptions.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="permit-num">03</div>
          <h3>When you can burn</h3>
          <p>
            Permits are valid between dawn and dusk on the day issued. Night burning is
            not authorized. Permits are not issued when the Fire Weather Index reaches <strong
              >Very High</strong
            > or <strong>Extreme</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="permit-num">04</div>
          <h3>Your responsibilities</h3>
          <p>
            A responsible adult must be present for the duration of the burn, with a
            charged hose or 20 gallons of water and a shovel on hand. The fire must be
            fully extinguished before you leave the site.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div style="margin-top: 64px;">
        <h3 style="font-size:28px;margin-bottom:24px">Common questions</h3>
        <details class="faq">
          <summary
            >How do I request a permit? <span class="plus" aria-hidden="true"
            ></span></summary
          >
          <div class="body">
            <p>
              Call the Fire Warden between 8:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. the day you intend to
              burn. Be ready to describe the location, size of the pile, and what you plan
              to burn. The Warden will check current conditions and either issue a permit
              verbally with a written copy to follow, or ask you to wait for a better day.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq">
          <summary>Is there a fee? <span class="plus" aria-hidden="true"></span></summary>
          <div class="body">
            <p>
              No. Permits are issued free of charge. Consider a donation to the department
              if you'd like to support our work.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq">
          <summary
            >Do I need a permit for a recreational campfire? <span
              class="plus"
              aria-hidden="true"></span></summary
          >
          <div class="body">
            <p>
              Not for a small, contained campfire (under 3 ft across) for warmth or
              cooking, provided it is in a fire ring, pit, or commercial fireplace. All
              other conditions &mdash; sober attendance, water on hand, fully extinguished
              &mdash; still apply.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq">
          <summary
            >What if my permit is suspended after it's issued? <span
              class="plus"
              aria-hidden="true"></span></summary
          >
          <div class="body">
            <p>
              If the Warden calls a suspension, extinguish your fire immediately and do
              not relight it. Your permit will be reissued the next permissible day at no
              cost. Suspensions are posted on this page and called out to active permit
              holders by phone.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="faq">
          <summary
            >I see smoke on my neighbor's property. Is that reportable? <span
              class="plus"
              aria-hidden="true"></span></summary
          >
          <div class="body">
            <p>
              If the fire appears unattended, is spreading, or is producing thick black or
              chemical-smelling smoke, call <strong>9-1-1</strong>. If you're unsure
              whether a neighbor has a permit, you may call the non-emergency line during
              daytime hours.
            </p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <!-- Contact card -->
      <div class="permit-contact">
        <div>
          <div class="mono" style="margin-bottom:8px">Request a permit</div>
          <h3>Call or email the Fire Warden</h3>
          <p>
            Day-of requests only. Leave a message if no answer and we will return your
            call within the hour during daylight.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="contacts">
          <div>
            <div class="k">Fire Warden</div>
            <a href="tel:8022352211">(802) 235-2211</a>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="k">Email</div>
            <a href="mailto:warden@irafd.vt.gov">warden@irafd.vt.gov</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

